the 2 status red warnings in place do not apply to galway.

column1: mouth cancer is an important global healthcare problem. there are more than 300 cases of cancer of the mouth (oral cavity and pharynx) reported in ireland every year. these cancers are more common in men than in women. however this is changing.

the incidence rate of cancer of the mouth in women has increased significantly at a rate of 3% per year since 1994. it mainly affects older people although younger people are being diagnosed now. in britain
column2: the incidence of mouth cancer has increased faster than any other cancer in the past 25 years.

column1: according to the national cancer registry in ireland
column2: roughly half of all mouth cancers and even less of cancers of the pharynx are diagnosed at an early stage.

column1: this can result in more complex treatment with greater impact on quality of life and overall survival. whilst it depends on the cancer site we know that more than half of those treated will have good survival outcomes and this continues to improve each year.
early detection of mouth cancer greatly improves the chances of survival.
dentists have a key role to play in the early detection of mouth cancer and in the prevention of the disease by identifying those patients who are exposed to risk factors.
